actual.comment:
Data on extension of cover vegetation of mangroves in Brazil and in Pilot Areas are under elaboration. CSR-IBAMA hired two professionals for the elaboration of final maps on mangroves in Brazil, they are validating field data and updating the 2013 mangroves map. Final output is expected by August 2015. During the present reporting time, the project supported staff of the CSR-IBAMA with in-the-field missions to mangroves areas, in order to check and validate some uncertain limits of the 2013 satellite map. The ongoing final phase includes: 

- Final map of mangroves area in Brazil;

- Mangroves geographic maps (states; municipalities; CUs) and thematic maps (shrimp culture; meta-analysis using some relevant maps available at the Brazilian Institute For Geography and Statistics – IBGE and at the Institute for Applied Economic Research - IPEA, such as HDI; demography; income; cash transfer programmes such as “Bolsa Familia”);

- Comparison with 2010 map of mangroves in Brazil, and evaluation of trends;

- Identification of salt flats and marshes (apicuns). This last parameter is critical for policy incidence and advocacy. Salt flats are part of mangrove ecosystem and they are critical for transition, renovation and expansion of mangroves, and the for health and resilience of the ecosystem. However they are slightly recognized in Brazilian legal framework (Resolution 303/2012 CONAMA) and are commonly exploited for shrimp culture and salt mines. This situation tends to deteriorate, as salt flats are threatened by the agribusiness sector interpretation of the Law 12.651/2012 (also called New Forest Code), which stipulates the possibility of increasing shrimp and salt production in those areas: 10% in Amazon biome and 35% in other biomes. An estimation of such expansion is not available yet, as it is the first apicuns mapping exercise.

